Data Analysis¶

Analysing Brands¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
ax = sns.countplot(y="Brand",data=df,palette="icefire")
for bars in ax.containers:
    ax.bar_label(bars)
plt.title("[No. of Phone Models by Brands]")
plt.xlabel("{Count}")
plt.ylabel("{Brand}")
plt.show()
  • Samsung have the most number of mobile phones followed by Apple and realme.

Analysing Most Costly Brands¶

In [ ]:
most_costly_brand = df.groupby(["Brand"],as_index=False)["Selling Price"].sum().sort_values(by="Selling Price",ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
sns.barplot(x="Brand",y="Selling Price",data=most_costly_brand,palette="cubehelix")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("[Pricing of Every Phone Brands]")
plt.xlabel("{Brand}")
plt.ylabel("{Selling Price}")
plt.show()
In [ ]:
plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 7))
sns.boxplot(x="Brand",y="Selling Price",data=df,palette="bright")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("[Pricing of Every Phone Brands]")
plt.xlabel("{Brand}")
plt.ylabel("{Selling Price}")
plt.show()
  • Apple is the most costly selling brand followed by Samsung.

Range Wise Analysis (Low Range(0-15000), Mid Range(16000-40000), Premium Range(above 40000) Smartphones)¶

In [ ]:
df["Price Range"] = pd.cut(df["Selling Price"], bins=[0, 15000, 40000, float("inf")], labels=["Lower Range", "Medium Range", "Premium Range"])
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
sns.countplot(x="Price Range",data=df,palette="coolwarm")
plt.title("[Different Price Range Counts of Phones]")
plt.xlabel("{Price Range}")
plt.ylabel("{Count}")
plt.show()
  • Most of the Smartphones belong to Lower Range Category(0-15000 Rs).

Average Selling Price of Each Brand¶

In [ ]:
avg_sp_bybrand = df.groupby(["Brand"], as_index=False)["Selling Price"].mean()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
sns.lineplot(x="Brand", y="Selling Price", data=avg_sp_bybrand, marker="o")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel("{Brand}")
plt.ylabel("{Average Selling Price of Phones}")
plt.title("[Average Price of Selling Phones by Brand]")
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()
  • Apple Brand has the Highest Average Selling Price among all, followed by Google Pixel.

Most Costly Selling Model in Each Brand¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(11.7, 7))
most_costly_model = df.loc[df.groupby("Brand")["Selling Price"].idxmax()]
most_costly_model["Brand_Model"] = most_costly_model["Brand"] + " - " + most_costly_model["Model"]
ax = sns.barplot(x="Brand_Model", y="Selling Price", data=most_costly_model, palette="Spectral")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
for i, j in enumerate(most_costly_model["Selling Price"]):
    ax.text(i, j, str(j), ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=10)
plt.xlabel("{Phone Model with Brand}")
plt.ylabel("{Selling Price}")
plt.title("[Most Costly Selling Phone Model in Each Brand]")
plt.show()

df[df['Discount Percentage']==df['Discount Percentage'].max()]

Conclusion :-¶

  • The availability of Lower Price Range Phones Should be Increased as most buyers buy phones in 15000 range.
  • Mean Rating is 4.24 STAR.
  • It is not True that only higher selling price products have a higher rating maximum mobiles lying between 0 to 25000 also have a Good Rating.
  • Vivo is providing more rated products and those are value for money also.
  • Apple is the most costly selling brand followed by Samsung.
  • Apple is the most Rated brand followed by Google Pixel.
  • Apple Brand has the Highest Average Selling Price among all, followed by Google Pixel and then followed by IQOO.
  • Samsung have the most number of mobile phones followed by Apple and realme.
  • GIONEE Brand is offering a 70.61% discount on Model "Pioneer P3" which is the highest discount percentage among all models.
  • Most of the Phones which are available with 4 GB RAM & 64 GB Storage.
  • Most Common Color offered is Black & Total number of Unique Colors for Phone Models are 637.
